{"mode": "overwrite", "content": "{
 "dialogue": [
   {
     "speaker": "SPEAKER_00",
     "text": "Welcome to episode 395. We're joined by Dr. Charles Chafin, whose work bridges psychology and financial planning.",
     "emo_text": "Warm introduction",
     "emo_alpha": 0.6,
     "source_segment_ids": ["seg_000", "seg_0004"]
   },
   {
     "speaker": "SPEAKER_00",
     "text": "Charles, can you talk about what role psychology plays in the financial planning process?",
     "emo_text": "Curious inquiry",
     "emo_alpha": 0.6,
     "source_segment_ids": ["seg_0006"]
   },
   {
     "speaker": "SPEAKER_02",
     "text": "It's a big role—it explains why clients behave the way they do with money. It bridges the gap between technical advice and real‑world behavior.",
     "emo_text": "Explaining",
     "emo_alpha": 0.6,
     "source_segment_ids": ["seg_0007"]
   },
   {
     "speaker": "SPEAKER_02",
     "text": "Our brains are designed for survival, not long‑term optimization. Money is like fire, and our brains are like toddlers—curious, impulsive, and focused on short‑term rewards.",
     "emo_text": "Analogical",
     "emo_alpha": 0.6,
     "source_segment_ids": ["seg_00013"]
   },
   {
     "speaker": "SPEAKER_00",
     "text": "How do cognitive biases and heuristics affect financial decision‑making?",
     "emo_text": "Follow‑up question",
     "emo_alpha": 0.6,
     "source_segment_ids": ["seg_00014"]
   },
   {
     "speaker": "SPEAKER_02",
     "text": "Heuristics are helpful shortcuts, but they create systematic errors like overconfidence or loss aversion. They get in the way of rational thinking, especially in the information age.",
     "emo_text": "Clarifying",
     "emo_alpha": 0.6,
     "source_segment_ids": ["seg_00015"]
   }
 ]
}"}

